owl:ObjectProperty.rdfs:comment:
Contiene_a
One geometry contains another if the other geometry is a subset of it and their interiors have at least one point in common. Contains is the inverse of Within.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Contains.html

Two polylines cross if they meet at points only, and at least one of the shared points is internal to both polylines. A polyline and polygon cross if a connected part of the polyline is partly inside and partly outside the polygon.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Crosses.html

Two geometries are disjoint if they don’t have any points in common. Disjoint is the inverse of Intersects. Disjoint is the most efficient operator and is guaranteed to work even on non-simple geometries.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Disjoint.html

Two geometries are equal if they occupy the same space.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Equals.html

One geometry is within another if it is a subset of the other geometry and their interiors have at least one point in common. Within is the inverse of Contains.
Contenido en. En ocasiones se utiliza el término "Within"
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Within.html

Two geometries intersect if they share at least one point in common.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Intersects.html (There is a conceptual mistake in the url of ESRI, when they say: "Intersects is the inverse of Disjoint")

Mereological relations
En filosofía, la mereología es el estudio de las relaciones entre partes, tanto de las partes con el todo, como de las partes con otras partes.
Tengo dudas en la relación que existe entre las relaciones "Mereological" con "inside" y "contains". Parecen ser equivalentes "isPartOf" con "inside" y "isWholeOf" con "contains" en http://kauppinen.net/tomi/kauppinen-xmlfinland2009.pdf hay ejemplos de relaciones Mereological.
No estoy seguro, pero la diferencia que noto es que las Mereological no están implicadas necesariamente por su ubicación espacial sino por su estructura organizacional. Pero por qué las ubican como relaciones espaciales en la literatura. Ejemplo tabla empresas y tabla trabajadores. Imaginen que los trabajadores están ubicados espacialmente. Un trabajador es parte de un empresa y la empresa tiene parte (has-part o isWholeOf) de ese trabador, pero el trabajador no hay una relación de ubicación espacial entre el trabajador y la empresa(relaciones "inside" y "contains")

Two geometries overlap if they have the same dimension, and their intersection also has the same dimension but is different from both of them.
Superposicion
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Overlaps.html

Two geometries touch if the intersection of their interiors is empty, but the intersection of the two geometries is not empty.
http://esri.github.io/geometry-api-java/doc/Touches.html

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shelf valley. a valley on the shelf, generally the shoreward extension of a canyon
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shelf-valley

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shoal. a surface-navigation hazard composed of unconsolidated material
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shoal

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shoal(s). a surface-navigation hazard composed of unconsolidated material
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shoal-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shoals. hazards to surface navigation composed of unconsolidated material
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shoals

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: The shop tag is used as a place of business that has stocked goods for sale. See the page titled Shop("http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Shop") for an introduction on its usage.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shop

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shore. a narrow zone bordering a waterbody which covers and uncovers at high and low water, respectively
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shore

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: shrine. a structure or place memorializing a person or religious concept
owl:Class.rdfs:label: shrine

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sill. the low part of a gap or saddle separating basins
sill. the low part of an underwater gap or saddle separating basins, including a similar feature at the mouth of a fjord
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sill

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sinkhole. a small crater-shape depression in a karst area
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sinkhole

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: slide. a mound of earth material, at the base of a slope and the associated scoured area
owl:Class.rdfs:label: slide

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: slope. the slope seaward from the shelf edge to the beginning of a continental rise or the point where there is a general reduction in slope
owl:Class.rdfs:label: slope

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: slope(s). a surface with a relatively uniform slope angle
owl:Class.rdfs:label: slope-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sluice. a conduit or passage for carrying off surplus water from a waterbody, usually regulated by means of a sluice gate
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sluice

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: snowfield. an area of permanent snow and ice forming the accumulation area of a glacier
owl:Class.rdfs:label: snowfield

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sound. or connecting two larger bodies of water"
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sound

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spa. a resort area usually developed around a medicinal spring
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spa

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: space center. a facility for launching, tracking, or controlling satellites and space vehicles
owl:Class.rdfs:label: space-center

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spillway. a passage or outlet through which surplus water flows over, around or through a dam
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spillway

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spit. a narrow, straight or curved continuation of a beach into a waterbody
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spit

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This is used to provide information about which sports are placed on a facility such as a pitch or stadium. See the page titled Sport("http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Sport") for an introduction on its usage.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sport

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spring(s). a place where ground water flows naturally out of the ground
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spring-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spur. a subordinate elevation, ridge, or rise projecting outward from a larger feature
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spur

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: spur(s). a subordinate ridge projecting outward from a hill, mountain or other elevation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: spur-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: square. a broad, open, public area near the center of a town or city
owl:Class.rdfs:label: square

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stable. a building for the shelter and feeding of farm animals, especially horses
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stable

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stadium. a structure with an enclosure for athletic games with tiers of seats for spectators
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stadium

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: steps. stones or slabs placed for ease in ascending or descending a steep slope
owl:Class.rdfs:label: steps

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stock route. a route taken by livestock herds
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stock-route

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stony desert. a desert plain characterized by a surface veneer of gravel and stones
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stony-desert

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: store. a building where goods and/or services are offered for sale
owl:Class.rdfs:label: store

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: storehouse. a building for storing goods, especially provisions
owl:Class.rdfs:label: storehouse

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: strait. a relatively narrow waterway, usually narrower and less extensive than a sound, connecting two larger bodies of water
owl:Class.rdfs:label: strait

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stream. a body of running water moving to a lower level in a channel on land
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stream

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stream bank. a sloping margin of a stream channel which normally confines the stream to its channel on land
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stream-bank

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stream bend. a conspicuously curved or bent segment of a stream
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stream-bend

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: stream mouth(s). a place where a stream discharges into a lagoon, lake, or the sea
owl:Class.rdfs:label: stream-mouth-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: street. a paved urban thoroughfare
owl:Class.rdfs:label: street

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sub-surface dam. a dam put down to bedrock in a sand river
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sub-surface-dam

owl:Class.rdfs:comment:
A distinct section of an urban settlement (city, town, etc.) with its own name and identity. e.g.
annexed towns or villages which were formerly independent, independent (or dependent) municipalities within a city or next to a much bigger town historical districts of settlements industrial districts or recreation areas within a settlements with specific names.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: suburb

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sugar mill. a facility where sugar cane is processed into raw sugar
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sugar-mill

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sugar plantation. an estate that specializes in growing sugar cane
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sugar-plantation

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sugar refinery. a facility for converting raw sugar into refined sugar
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sugar-refinery

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: sulphur spring(s). a place where sulphur ground water flows naturally out of the ground
owl:Class.rdfs:label: sulphur-spring-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: swamp. a wetland dominated by tree vegetation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: swamp

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tablemount (or guyot). a seamount having a comparatively smooth, flat top
tablemounts (or guyots). seamounts having a comparatively smooth, flat top
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tablemount

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: talus slope. a steep concave slope formed by an accumulation of loose rock fragments at the base of a cliff or steep slope
owl:Class.rdfs:label: talus-slope

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tank farm. a tract of land occupied by large, cylindrical, metal tanks in which oil or liquid petrochemicals are stored
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tank-farm

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tea plantation. an estate which specializes in growing tea bushes
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tea-plantation

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: technical school. post-secondary school with a specifically technical or vocational curriculum
owl:Class.rdfs:label: technical-school

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: temp work office. Temporary Work Offices
owl:Class.rdfs:label: temp-work-office

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: temple(s). an edifice dedicated to religious worship
owl:Class.rdfs:label: temple-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: terrace. a long, narrow alluvial platform bounded by steeper slopes above and below, usually overlooking a waterbody

terrace. a relatively flat horizontal or gently inclined surface, sometimes long and narrow, which is bounded by a steeper ascending slope on one side and by a steep descending slope on the opposite side
owl:Class.rdfs:label: terrace

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: territory.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: territory

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: theater. A building, room, or outdoor structure for the presentation of plays, films, or other dramatic performances
owl:Class.rdfs:label: theater

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: third-order administrative division. a subdivision of a second-order administrative division
owl:Class.rdfs:label: third-order-administrative-division

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tidal creek(s). a meandering channel in a coastal wetland subject to bi-directional tidal currents
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tidal-creek-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tidal flat(s). a large flat area of mud or sand attached to the shore and alternately covered and uncovered by the tide
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tidal-flat-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tomb(s). a structure for interring bodies
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tomb-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tongue. an elongate (tongue-like) extension of a flat sea floor into an adjacent higher feature
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tongue

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: This is used to map places and things of specific interest to tourists. For example these may be places to see, places to stay and things and places providing support. See the page titled Tourism("http://wiki.openstreetmap.org/wiki/Tourism") for an introduction on its usage.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tourism

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tower. a high conspicuous structure, typically much higher than its diameter
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tower

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: A second tier urban settlement of local importance, often with a population of 10,000 people and good range of local facilities including schools, medical facilities etc and traditionally a market. In areas of low population, towns may have significantly lower populations. See neighbourhood and possibly also suburb on how to tag divisions within a town.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: town

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: traffic circle. a road junction formed around a central circle about which traffic moves in one direction only
owl:Class.rdfs:label: traffic-circle

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: trail. a path, track, or route used by pedestrians, animals, or off-road vehicles
owl:Class.rdfs:label: trail

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: transit terminal. facilities for the handling of vehicular freight and passengers
owl:Class.rdfs:label: transit-terminal

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tree(s). a conspicuous tree used as a landmark
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tree-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: trench. a long, narrow, characteristically very deep and asymmetrical depression of the sea floor, with relatively steep sides
owl:Class.rdfs:label: trench

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: triangulation station. a point on the earth whose position has been determined by triangulation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: triangulation-station

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tribal area. a tract of land used by nomadic or other tribes
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tribal-area

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: trough. a long depression of the sea floor characteristically flat bottomed and steep sided, and normally shallower than a trench
owl:Class.rdfs:label: trough

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tundra. a marshy, treeless, high latitude plain, dominated by mosses, lichens, and low shrub vegetation under permafrost conditions
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tundra

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: tunnel. a subterranean passageway for transportation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: tunnel

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: underground irrigation canal(s). a gently inclined underground tunnel bringing water for irrigation from aquifers
owl:Class.rdfs:label: underground-irrigation-canal-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: underground lake. a standing body of water in a cave
owl:Class.rdfs:label: underground-lake

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: united states government establishment. a facility operated by the United States Government in Panama
owl:Class.rdfs:label: united-states-government-establishment

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: university. An institution for higher learning with teaching and research facilities constituting a graduate school and professional schools that award master's degrees and doctorates and an undergraduate division that awards bachelor's degrees.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: university

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: university prep school. University Preparation Schools & Institutions
owl:Class.rdfs:label: university-prep-school

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: upland. an extensive interior region of high land with low to moderate surface relief
owl:Class.rdfs:label: upland

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: valley. a relatively shallow, wide depression, the bottom of which usually has a continuous gradient
valley. an elongated depression usually traversed by a stream
owl:Class.rdfs:label: valley

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: veterinary facility. a building or camp at which veterinary services are available
owl:Class.rdfs:label: veterinary-facility

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: vineyard. a planting of grapevines
owl:Class.rdfs:label: vineyard

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: volcano. a conical elevation composed of volcanic materials with a crater at the top
owl:Class.rdfs:label: volcano

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wadi. found primarily in North Africa and the Middle East"
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wadi

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wadi bend. a conspicuously curved or bent segment of a wadi
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wadi-bend

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wadi junction. a place where two or more wadies join
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wadi-junction

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wadi mouth. the lower terminus of a wadi where it widens into an adjoining floodplain, depression, or waterbody
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wadi-mouth

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wadies. found primarily in North Africa and the Middle East"
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wadies

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wall. a thick masonry structure, usually enclosing a field or building, or forming the side of a structure
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wall

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: water mill. a mill powered by running water
owl:Class.rdfs:label: water-mill

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: water pumping station. a facility for pumping water from a major well or through a pipeline
owl:Class.rdfs:label: water-pumping-station

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: water tank. a contained pool or tank of water at, below, or above ground level
owl:Class.rdfs:label: water-tank

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: watercourse. a natural, well-defined channel produced by flowing water, or an artificial channel designed to carry flowing water
owl:Class.rdfs:label: watercourse

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: waterfall(s). a perpendicular or very steep descent of the water of a stream
owl:Class.rdfs:label: waterfall-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: waterhole(s). a natural hole, hollow, or small depression that contains water, used by man and animals, especially in arid areas
owl:Class.rdfs:label: waterhole-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: waterworks. a facility for supplying potable water through a water source and a system of pumps and filtration beds
owl:Class.rdfs:label: waterworks

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: weir(s). a small dam in a stream, designed to raise the water level or to divert stream flow through a desired channel
owl:Class.rdfs:label: weir-s-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: well. a cylindrical hole, pit, or tunnel drilled or dug down to a depth from which water, oil, or gas can be pumped or brought to the surface
owl:Class.rdfs:label: well

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wetland. an area subject to inundation, usually characterized by bog, marsh, or swamp vegetation
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wetland

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: whaling station. a facility for butchering whales and processing train oil
owl:Class.rdfs:label: whaling-station

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wharf(-ves). a structure of open rather than solid construction along a shore or a bank which provides berthing for ships and cargo-handling facilities
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wharf--ves-

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: whirlpool. a turbulent, rotating movement of water in a stream
owl:Class.rdfs:label: whirlpool

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wildlife reserve. a tract of public land reserved for the preservation of wildlife
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wildlife-reserve

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: windmill. a mill or water pump powered by wind
owl:Class.rdfs:label: windmill

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: wreck. the site of the remains of a wrecked vessel
owl:Class.rdfs:label: wreck

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: zone.
owl:Class.rdfs:label: zone

owl:Class.rdfs:comment: zoo. a zoological garden or park where wild animals are kept for exhibition
owl:Class.rdfs:label: zoo
